ch 3 summary:
1. The Core Purpose of a Database
 Two Operations: Stores data when given (db_set), and returns data when asked
(db_get).
 Developer Insight: Understanding internal storage allows you to choose and tune the
right engine for your specific workload (Transactional vs. Analytics).
2. The Simplest Database: Append-only Log
 Write Performance: Excellent O(1) because appending sequentially to the end of a file
is the simplest and most efficient operation.
 Read Performance: Terrible O(n) because it requires scanning the entire file from
beginning to end to locate a key.
 The Log Concept: An append-only sequence of records. It does not have to be human-
readable; it can be binary.
3. The Index: The Trade-off
 Definition: An additional metadata structure derived from the primary data to act as a
signpost.
 The Core Trade-off: Well-chosen indexes speed up read queries significantly, but every
index slows down writes because it must be updated whenever data is written.
 Constraint: Databases do not index everything by default; developers must manually
choose indexes based on application query patterns.
4. Hash Indexes (e.g., Bitcask)
 How it works: An in-memory hash map maps keys directly to byte offsets in an
append-only disk file. Used as the default engine in Riak.
 Compaction & Merging: The log is split into immutable segments. Compaction drops
duplicate keys, keeping only the latest update. Merging happens in a background
thread.
Real-world Mechanics:
 File Format: Uses a binary format encoding string length first (faster than CSV).
 Deleting: Appends a tombstone record to tell the merging process to discard older
values.
 Recovery: Stores a snapshot of the hash map on disk so it doesn't have to rebuild it by
scanning segments on crash.
 Crashes: Uses checksums to detect and ignore partially written or corrupted records.
 Concurrency: Uses a single writer thread but allows multiple concurrent readers
(since segments are immutable).
Limitations:
1. All keys must fit in RAM.
2. Range queries are highly inefficient (each key must be looked up individually).
5. SSTables and LSM-Trees
 SSTable: Segments sorted by key and unique.
o Mergesort: Side-by-side merging; most recent value wins.
o Sparse Index: RAM holds landmark keys; scans a tiny disk block sequentially.
o Compression: Blocks compressed to save I/O bandwidth and space.
 LSM-Trees Order:
o Memtable: Balanced in-memory tree (Red-Black/AVL) that keeps writes sorted.
o Write Workflow: Writes go to Memtable, then flush to an on-disk SSTable once
a size threshold is passed
o Read Workflow: Checks Memtable first, then the most recent SSTable, and
finally older SSTables.
o WAL: Unsorted disk log used to restore the Memtable after a crash; discarded
after a flush.
o Apps: LevelDB, RocksDB, Cassandra, HBase, and Lucene (for term dictionaries)
 Optimizations:
o Bloom Filters: Instantly flag if a key does not exist, preventing wasteful disk
reads.
o Compaction: Size-tiered (HBase: small merged into large) vs. Leveled
(LevelDB: key ranges split across incremental "levels").
6. B-Trees (The Standard)
 The Standard: Dominant relational index that breaks the database into fixed-size pages
(usually 4 KB).
 Structure: * Root Page: The starting point of a query containing range boundaries.
o Branching Factor: The number of child page pointers per page (typically several
hundred).
o Leaf Page: The bottom level holding individual keys and inline values or
references.
 Page Splitting: A full page splits into two half-full pages during insertion, updating the
parent. Tree depth remains balanced at O(log n).
 Crash Resilience (WAL): Splits risk index corruption on crash. WAL (Redo Log) logs
all modifications on disk before updating tree pages to restore state safely.
 Concurrency: Structure is protected with latches (lightweight locks) to control thread
access.
Optimizations:
1. Copy-on-Write (e.g., LMDB): Writes modified pages to a new location instead of
overwriting in-place.
2. Key Abbreviation: Truncates keys in interior pages to pack more boundaries, increasing
the branching factor.
3. Sibling Pointers: Direct links between adjacent leaf pages for fast sequential scanning
without jumping back to parents
7. Comparing B-Trees and LSM-Trees
 Rule of Thumb: LSM is faster for writes; B-Trees are faster for reads.
 LSM Pros: * Lower write amplification (sequential writes vs. B-Tree WAL and page
overwrites).
o Better compression with no page fragmentation.
 LSM Cons: * Compaction depletes disk resources, stalling concurrent queries.
o High write throughput starves bandwidth, risking unmerged segment growth and
disk exhaustion.
o No automatic write throttling exists.
8. Other Indexing Structures
 Secondary Indexes: Crucial for joins; keys are not unique (solved by mapping a key to
a list of row IDs). Both B-Trees and LSM-Trees can serve here.
 Index Values Storage:
o Heap File: Stores rows in no particular order in a separate file; indexes just point
to heap locations to avoid data duplication.
o Clustered Index: Stores the actual row data directly inside the primary key index
(e.g., MySQL InnoDB).
o Covering Index: Stores specific table columns within the index to answer queries
directly without a secondary heap hop.
 Multi-Column Indexes:
o Concatenated Index: Appends fields sequentially into one key (e.g., lastname,
firstname). Inefficient if searching only by the second column.
o Multi-Dimensional Indexes: Used for simultaneous multi-column or geospatial
range queries (e.g., R-Trees for map coordinates). Standard 1D B-Trees cannot
do this efficiently.
 Fuzzy Indexes: Used for non-exact values like typos or synonyms. Lucene handles
typos via an in-memory automaton using Levenshtein edit distance.
9. Keeping Everything in Memory (In-Memory Databases)
 The Concept: Datasets kept entirely in RAM because cost-per-gigabyte has eroded.
 Durability: Disk acts solely as append-only log/snapshot for durability; reads are
served purely from memory (e.g., VoltDB, Redis).
 The Real Performance Factor: Faster because they avoid the CPU overhead of
encoding and serializing data structures into disk layouts (not just because they avoid
disk reads).
 Anti-Caching: Supports datasets larger than RAM by evicting least recently used data to
disk at a single-record granularity when memory is full.
10. Transaction Processing (OLTP) vs. Analytics (OLAP)
 OLTP (Online Transaction Processing): User-facing, interactive, high volume of
requests. Queries look up small records via a key. Disk seek time is the bottleneck.
 OLAP (Online Analytic Processing): Internal business analysts; low volume of
complex queries. Scans millions of records to compute aggregations like SUM or AVG.
Disk bandwidth is the bottleneck.
 Data Warehouse: A separate database containing a read-only copy of OLTP data,
optimized specifically for analytics without harming live production performance.
 ETL (Extract-Transform-Load): The process of extracting data from OLTP systems,
transforming it into an analysis-friendly schema, and loading it into the warehouse.
11. Stars and Snowflakes: Schemas for Analytics
 Star Schema (Dimensional Modeling): * Fact Table: At the center; extremely large
table where each row represents an individual event/transaction (holds numeric attributes
+ foreign keys to dimensions).
o Dimension Tables: Surround the fact table like rays of a star, representing the
who, what, where, when, how, and why of the event.
 Snowflake Schema: A variation where dimension tables are further broken down and
normalized into subdimensions. Star schema is usually preferred for simplicity.
12. Column-Oriented Storage
 The Concept: Row-oriented OLTP is inefficient for analytics because it loads entire
100+ attribute rows. Column-oriented storage stores all values from each individual
column together in separate files; queries only read columns they use, saving disk
throughput.
 Bitmap Encoding: Maps column values into separate bitmaps (1 if row matches, 0 if
not); sparse bitmaps are run-length encoded for extreme compression.
 Vectorized Processing: Query engines process chunks of compressed columns directly
fitting in CPU L1 cache, executing operations via SIMD instructions in tight loops
without function calls.
 Writes (LSM Integration): Real-time updates are impossible with compressed columns.
All writes go to an in-memory sorted structure and are later merged with disk files in bulk
using LSM concepts.
13. Materialized Views & Data Cubes
 Materialized View: A disk-persisted copy of query aggregate results; updated when data
changes (too expensive for OLTP, used in read-heavy OLAP).
 Data Cube (OLAP Cube): A multi-dimensional grid of precomputed aggregates grouped by
separate dimensions.
o Trade-off: Queries are extremely fast (precomputed), but lack the flexibility of
raw transaction data